    <meta name="dc.description" content="This work presents a mathematical solution to data privacy and integrity issues in Split Learning which uses Homomorphic Encryption (HE) and Zero-Knowledge Proofs (ZKP). It allows calculations to be conducted on encrypted data, keeping the data private, while ZKP ensures the correctness of these calculations without revealing the underlying data. Our proposed system, HavenSL, combines HE and ZKP to provide strong protection against attacks. It uses Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT) to analyze model updates in the frequency domain to detect unusual changes in parameters. HavenSL also has a rollback feature that brings the system back to a verified state if harmful changes are detected. Experiments on CIFAR-10, MNIST, and Fashion-MNIST datasets show that using Homomorphic Encryption and Zero-Knowledge Proofs during training is feasible and accuracy is maintained. This mathematical-based approach shows how crypto-graphic can protect decentralized learning systems. It also proves the practical use of HE and ZKP in secure, privacy-aware collaborative AI." >

